 and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Either a revival of the medieval given name, a pet form of   Walter   (from   Wat   + the diminutive suffix <i>-kin</i>), or a transferred use of the surname derived from it."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Roper","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From an Old French personal name, <i>Rog(i)er</i>, of Germanic (Frankish) origin, from <i>hrōd</i> ‘fame’ + <i>gār</i>, <i>gēr</i> ‘spear’. This was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain, replacing the native Old English form <i>Hrōðgār</i>. <i>Roger</i> was one of the most popular boys' names throughout the medieval period, but less so after the Reformation, though it has continued in regular use to the present day.  Roger, Count of Sicily  (  <i>c.</i>1031–1101 ), son of Tancred, recovered Sicily from the Arabs. His son, also called Roger, ruled Sicily as king, presiding over a court noted for its splendour and patronage of the arts."],"variants":[{"name":"Rodger","meanings":["Variant spelling of   Roger  , in part from the surname derived from the given name in the Middle Ages."]}]},{"name":"Vychan","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Welsh: A Welsh name of great antiquity, from vyckan, little, small; i.e. small in stature. Compare the surname Bychan and the Armoric Le Bihan."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Anne ferch Watkin Roper Vychan was born about 1465, in Glamorgan, Wales, her father, Watkin Roper Vychan, was 27 and her mother, Mrs. Watkin Roper VYCHAN, was 27. She married Rees Lloyd about 1483, in Glamorgan, Wales, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1465–":"umbes 1465–Surnud","1465–Female":"1465–Surnud","1463–Male":"1463–Surnud","1490–1520":"1490–1520","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1440–Female":"1440–Surnud","Abt 1483":"umbes 1483","Abt 1465":"umbes 1465","Abt 1464":"umbes 1464","1520":"1520","1465":"1465","1463":"1463","1440":"1440",